Deceased","1468":"1468","1500":"1500","1465":"1465","1530":"1530","1480":"1480","Roman Empire":"Roman Empire","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Baillie","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish:","from Older Scots <i>baillie</i>, <i>baili</i>. In Scotland, a baillie was a status name for any of various officials, including the chief magistrate in a barony and (later) the chief magistrate or administrative officer of a barony or district. Etymologically, this is the same word as English   Bailey  , but the functions as well as the spelling of the two officials were different in England and Scotland.","topographic name from Older Scots <i>bailli</i> ‘outer court of a castle’; see   Bailey   3 and   Bale   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Bailie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Baillie  ."]},{"name":"Bailey","meanings":["English: status name for a steward or official, from Middle English <i>bailli</i> ‘manager, administrator’ (Old French <i>baillis</i>, from Late Latin <i>baiulivus</i>, an adjectival derivative of <i>baiulus</i> ‘attendant, carrier, porter’).","English: habitational name from Bailey in Little Mitton, Lancashire, named with Old English <i>beg</i> ‘berry’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","English: occasionally a topographic name for someone who lived by the outer wall of a castle, from Middle English (Old French) <i>bailli</i> ‘outer courtyard of a castle’ (Old French <i>bail(le)</i> ‘enclosure’, a derivative of <i>bailer</i> ‘to enclose’). This term became a placename in its own right, denoting a district beside a fortification or wall, as in the case of the Old Bailey in London, which formed part of the early medieval outer wall of the city."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When 7th of Lamington William Baillie was born in 1500, his father, 6th of Lamington William Baillie, was 32 and his mother, Elizabeth Lindsay, was 35. He had at least 1 son with Jean Hamilton."},"et":{"1500–":"1500–Surnud","1500–Male":"1500–Surnud","1480–Female":"1480–Surnud","1530–Male":"1530–Surnud","1468–Male":"1468–Surnud","1465–Female":"1465–Surnud","1468":"1468","1500":"1500","1465":"1465","1530":"1530","1480":"1480","Roman Empire":"Roman Empire"},"fi":{"1500–":"1500–Kuollut","1500–Male":"1500–Kuollut","1480–Female":"1480–Kuollut","1530–Male":"1530–Kuollut","1468–Male":"1468–Kuollut","1465–Female":"1465–Kuollut","1468":"1468","1500":"1500","1465":"1465","1530":"1530","1480":"1480","Roman Empire":"Roman Empire"},"fr":{"1500–":"1500–Décédé","1500–Male":"1500–Décédé","1480–Female":"1480–Décédée","1530–Male":"1530–Décédé","1468–Male":"1468–Décédé","1465–Female":"1465–Décédée","1468":"1468","1500":"1500","1465":"1465","1530":"1530","1480":"1480","Roman Empire":"Roman Empire","lifeSummary":"Lorsque 7th of Lamington William Baillie est né en 1500, son père, 6th of Lamington William Baillie, avait 32 ans et sa mère, Elizabeth Lindsay, avait 35 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Jean Hamilton."},"de":{"1500–":"1500–Verstorben","1500–Male":"1500–Verstorben","1480–Female":"1480–Verstorben","1530–Male":"1530–Verstorben","1468–Male":"1468–Verstorben","1465–Female":"1465–Verstorben","1468":"1468","1500":"1500","1465":"1465","1530":"1530","148